I've posted about this before, but John Graunt, the literal inventor of epidemiology and demographics as sciences, was highly skeptical of the reported numbers for bubonic plague deaths and claimed the corpse collectors/coroners were misinterpreting the cause of death of the dead

The book was "Natural and Political Observations Made upon the Bills of Mortality" published in 1662 and he basically speculated that they had reclassified the deaths from liver inflammation, "spleen", etc. and rebranded them as plague deaths to push up the numbers. Same as 2020.
The father of antivaxxers and covid skeptics

A few excerpts from Captain John Graunt's book's Index:

- "The troublesome seclusions in the Plague-time are not a remedy to be purchased at vast inconveniences."

- "Alterations in the Air do incomparably more operate as to the Plague, than the Contagion of Converse."

- "Purples, Small-Pox, and other malignant Diseases, fore-run the Plague."

- "The more sickly the year is, the less fertile of Births."

- "In London there have been 12 Burials for 11 Christnings."

- "in the Country there have been, contrariwise, 63 Christnings for 52 Burials."

His basic observations are that no one understands how the plague or disease in general works and nothing done about them influences their cyclical patterns whatsoever. And that people multiply in the country and then move to the big city en masse and die out there. 17th century.

John Graunt doubts the diagnoses of "death of old age" and says they are probably matter of subjective judgement of the coroners, even if in old age there was a loss of "Innate Heat" (metabolic decline). Dr. Hans Selye also didn't believe in deaths of old age, always a real cause
